Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members to the board of the U.S. central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives people in America – and the U.S. Congress – an opportunity to reflect on the most important central bank in the world and its future course.
The obvious, first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to so completely miss its most important mandate—ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Institutional self-examination is certainly appropriate now.
Yet while monetary policy is making headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether they will use their enormous power to advance climate or social policy.
For example, the Fed could deny credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, require banks to grant loans only to companies with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit toward desired alternatives.
Moreover, they could decide to explicitly conduct their regulatory activities in the name of equality or ethnic justice by mandating banks where and to whom loans should be granted, who should be hired and who should be fired, and so on.
Yet before we address the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move in, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In 2008, the U.S. government made a momentous decision: although financial institutions could still largely obtain the money for risky investments by selling short-term, run-prone debt instruments, swarms of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the risk vulnerability of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large chunks of the magnitude of subprime mortgages in the banks' balance sheets.
Yet during the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually occurred at the beginning of 2020, the Fed discarded its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even larger scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for plain vanilla U.S. government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been postponed.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed once again rescued the money market funds.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never came to that.
In addition, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially offering a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the U.S. Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the rescue package for the financial sector—the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in 2020, with the "Powell put"—among other measures—explicit lower bounds for corporate bond prices were introduced.
The predictable reply to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of relief measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply put out any new crisis with a new flood of money.
The problem, however, lies in the incentives created by these strategies.
Why go to the trouble of using liquidity provisions, or measures such as buying at falling prices, or treating a "distress sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will inevitably outperform them all and collect the profits.
Why would a company still issue shares when it could simply take out a loan, knowing that the state supports the debt or helps the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why do investors hesitate to buy dubious securities when their value is guaranteed in tough times by the Fed's additional "whatever it takes" promise?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will bear the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, state pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
Yet each new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will finally refuse to invest more money in rescue efforts, and people will not be happy with billions of newly printed money.
If the rescue packages expected by everyone do not materialize, we will wake up to a major crisis – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulatory authorities and lawmakers at least still recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap the profits while in bad times taxpayers would have to cover the losses.
In the year 2020, people indulged in self-satisfaction regarding the rescue operations.
Exactly the Fed that in 2008 failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages just as it failed to foresee the pandemic of 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests with regard to "climate risks," will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask about the mentioned events.
And although jargon such as "networking," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to actually define the term "systemic" risk, except that it has become a catch-all term that grants regulatory authorities comprehensive power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to foresee risks, accurately assess the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that enormous debts can always be repaid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always steps in to bail out huge debts during bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it claims that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans little.
However, she is based on the wrong cause.
An immense effort to comply with regulations represents a major barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is senseless.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of unintended consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to have prophetic abilities.
Scandalously, the Fed has blocked companies in the Narrow Banking sector and payment service providers that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before she commits herself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it is fulfilling its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
